<h2>Travel</h2>

<p>I suffer from chronic wanderlust. These sites will direct you to some of my favorite travel experiences.</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="http://www.gate-travel.org" target="_blank">Global Awareness Through Experience, Mexico and Central America</a> - Directed by Marie Des Jarlais and Cecilia Corcoran, Global Awareness Through Experience (GATE)</a> operates tours of Latin America and Eastern Europe that focus on social justice issues. Not your average tour, you get to meet real people and see life how it is really lived by people in these countries. Ceci, Marie and their collaborators in Mexico and Guatemala have had a profound influence on my worldview. They provide unique opportunities for photography as well.</li>
<li><a href="http://www.kihealthretreat.com" target="_blank">Kangaroo Island Health Retreat, Australia</a> - During the summer of 2002 I was fast approaching burn-out. As it happened I had an August business trip scheduled for Australia. Deciding to combine a little R&R with work, I booked into the Kangaroo Island Health Retreat for a week, and it turned my physical and mental health around. Retreat owner and director Sue McCarthy runs a practical, pragmatic and effective program to start on the road to improving your health.</li>
<li><a href="http://www.achill247.com" target="_blank">Achill Island, Ireland</a> - In February and March 1996 I spent 40 days (and 40 nights) on Achill Island (<asp:HyperLink runat="server" NavigateUrl="~/Musings.aspx">read my Achill Island Essays</asp:HyperLink>). Situated on Southern Ireland's west coast, it provided the solitude I needed for my self-led retreat (in February and March that is. During the summer it's a popular holiday destination). Achill Island has inspired generations of artists, writers and poets.</li>
</ul>

